    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on a thorough review of the provided filing excerpts, here is a summary of the specific, quantitative commitments and the nature of the disclosures for **The Algorithm** and **Terafab**.\n\n### **Terafab**\nThe filing provides one major quantitative target but deliberately withholds specific timelines, financial details, and project milestones.\n\n*   **Quantitative Capacity Target:** The **only hard number** disclosed is the **long-term production goal for Terafab: "one terawatt of annual compute production capacity."** This figure is stated repeatedly across multiple sections of the preamble.\n*   **Forward-Looking Targets & Projections:**\n    *   **Product Types:** The facility aims to produce two types of chips: one optimized for terrestrial use (e.g., for Tesla\'s Optimus robots and vehicles) and another optimized for the space environment for SpaceX\'s orbital compute.\n    *   **Strategic Goals:** The initiative is expected to "alleviate potential future chip shortages at SpaceX," "optimize compute performance," "potentially reduce overall compute costs," and provide "speed and cost advantages from vertical integration."\n*   **Missing Hard Numbers (Explicitly Not Disclosed):**\n    *   **Completion Dates/Timelines:** The filing explicitly states: "Any specific projects undertaken pursuant to this framework will be subject to separate negotiations and agreements **(including any development timelines...)** and **have not yet been determined**."\n    *   **Capital Expenditures:** No capex figures are provided. The filing confirms details are pending separate agreements.\n    *   **Revenue Targets:** No revenue projections are associated with Terafab.\n    *   **Intermediate Capacity Milestones:** There are no phased targets (e.g., gigawatts per year) before the 1 TW annual goal.\n    *   **Financial Terms:** Specific financial terms of the collaboration with Tesla and Intel are not finalized.\n\n### **The Algorithm**\nThis is disclosed as an operational philosophy, not a metric-driven program. The filing provides no quantitative KPIs for it.\n\n*   **Definition:** "The Algorithm" is described as a **five-step iterative process**: 1) make requirements less dumb, 2) delete unnecessary parts/processes, 3) optimize what remains, 4) accelerate cycle time, and 5) automate proven processes.\n*   **Nature of Disclosure:** It is presented as a **guiding principle** and "cultural and operational standard of excellence" that has defined SpaceX. It is **not framed as a target with specific, measurable outcomes or KPIs** in the provided excerpts.\n\n### **Other Relevant Quantitative Data in the Filing (Context)**\nWhile not part of Terafab or The Algorithm, the filing provides measurable metrics for existing infrastructure that sets the context:\n*   **COLOSSUS Clusters:** Approximately **1.0 gigawatt** of compute power collectively.\n*   **Deployment Speed:** COLOSSUS first cluster online in **122 days**; COLOSSUS II first cluster online in **91 days**.\n*   **X/Grok User Metrics:** Over **1.3 billion** supported accounts active in the last 12 months; approximately **550 million** MAUs; approximately **117 million** MAUs using Grok features.\n\n**Conclusion:** The filing discloses a single, ambitious **quantitative target for Terafab: 1 terawatt of annual production capacity**. However, it explicitly states that **specific timelines, capital expenditure amounts, project milestones, and revenue targets for Terafab have not been determined** and will be subject to future agreements. For **"The Algorithm,"** no quantitative targets or KPIs are provided; it is described solely as an operational methodology.',
